00:16:20,000 --> 00:16:24,000
 And they were just amazed at the ability of these animals that typically eat krill

261
00:16:24,000 --> 00:16:29,000
 and just run it through its system and process it that way,

262
00:16:29,000 --> 00:16:31,000
 had swallowed something like a giant squid.

263
00:16:31,000 --> 00:16:33,000
 All that to say, I've seen a whale up close.

264
00:16:33,000 --> 00:16:36,000
 Let me just tell you, it can swallow you.

265
00:16:36,000 --> 00:16:37,000
 But here's the deal.

266
00:16:37,000 --> 00:16:41,000
 Could you live, if you were in the belly of a whale, three days like Jonah was?

267
00:16:41,000 --> 00:16:43,000
 I'm going to make a case that Jonah didn't need to live for three days

268
00:16:43,000 --> 00:16:44,000
 in the belly of a whale.

269
00:16:44,000 --> 00:16:49,000
 I'm going to make a case that it wouldn't surprise me at all if he died.

270
00:16:49,000 --> 00:16:53,000
 And God raised him from the dead three days later when he was regurgitated by that whale.

271
00:16:53,000 --> 00:16:55,000
 I don't really need to figure it out.

272
00:16:55,000 --> 00:16:57,000
 I guess if God wanted him to be in that first little stomach,

273
00:16:57,000 --> 00:17:02,000
 and scientists will tell you that different amounts of food are moved in different directions,

274
00:17:02,000 --> 00:17:07,000
 that Jonah, for whatever reason, was not processed by that whale

275
00:17:07,000 --> 00:17:12,000
 and was three days in the deep, Jesus said, not just Jonah in the story.

276
00:17:12,000 --> 00:17:15,000
 It's in the Old Testament, but Jesus said, I'm going to give you a sign.

277
00:17:15,000 --> 00:17:17,000
 It's going to be the sign of Jonah,

278
00:17:17,000 --> 00:17:20,000
 that a man will be three days in the deep, in the dark,

279
00:17:20,000 --> 00:17:23,000
 and will raise again to proclaim to you amazing news.

280
00:17:23,000 --> 00:17:25,000
 Now, here's something else that's kind of crazy,

281
00:17:25,000 --> 00:17:32,000
 is that the people that Jonah was told to go and share the story of repentance with,

282
00:17:32,000 --> 00:17:34,000
 that there was a God that does exist in the heavens,

283
00:17:34,000 --> 00:17:36,000
 that people are going to have to do business with,

284
00:17:36,000 --> 00:17:38,000
 he was called to go to the Ninevites.

285
00:17:38,000 --> 00:17:40,000
 The Ninevites were the most awful people in the face of the earth.

286
00:17:40,000 --> 00:17:42,000
 They were the enemies of the nation of Israel,

287
00:17:42,000 --> 00:17:44,000
 and Jonah knew that God was merciful,

288
00:17:44,000 --> 00:17:48,000
 and he wanted nothing to do with that message going to those Assyrians.

289
00:17:48,000 --> 00:17:51,000
 Assyrians were notoriously evil.

290
00:17:51,000 --> 00:17:54,000
 They were, in fact, the very first well-known terrorists.

291
00:17:54,000 --> 00:17:56,000
 They didn't just seek to conquer lands.

292
00:17:56,000 --> 00:18:00,000
 They sought to conquer lands by terror.

293
00:18:00,000 --> 00:18:04,000
 They would run poles through their enemies,

294
00:18:04,000 --> 00:18:07,000
 up through their backside, through their gill, if you will,

295
00:18:07,000 --> 00:18:10,000
 their jaw, and they would use them to light their way.

296
00:18:10,000 --> 00:18:12,000
 They would take the skins of their enemies,

297
00:18:12,000 --> 00:18:16,000
 and they would use them to provide further rain, if you will,

298
00:18:16,000 --> 00:18:18,000
 resistance to their tents.

299
00:18:18,000 --> 00:18:20,000
 They would cut the heads off their enemies,

300
00:18:20,000 --> 00:18:24,000
 and they would stack them up like cannonballs in pyramids.

301
00:18:24,000 --> 00:18:26,000
 And they wouldn't just defeat you.

302
00:18:26,000 --> 00:18:28,000
 They would terrorize you.

303
00:18:28,000 --> 00:18:32,000
 And they were hated by all nations, feared by all nations,

304
00:18:32,000 --> 00:18:37,000
 and Jonah, when he heard word that God wanted him to go and proclaim

305
00:18:37,000 --> 00:18:46,000
 the message of forgiveness and redemption and reconciliation to him,

306
00:18:46,000 --> 00:18:48,000
 Jonah said, "I'm not going there."

307
00:18:48,000 --> 00:18:50,000
 Whether he was scared to go there

308
00:18:50,000 --> 00:18:54,000
 or whether he just didn't want those enemies to experience grace,

309
00:18:54,000 --> 00:18:55,000
 it doesn't matter.

310
00:18:55,000 --> 00:18:57,000
 He decided to go the opposite direction.

311
00:18:57,000 --> 00:19:00,000
 Let's read the story of Jonah,

312
00:19:00,000 --> 00:19:03,000
 and I think you're going to find some application

313
00:19:03,000 --> 00:19:05,000
 that will encourage you tonight.

314
00:19:05,000 --> 00:19:13,000
 Jonah 1 says, "The word of the Lord came to Jonah, saying,

315
00:19:13,000 --> 00:19:18,000
 'Arise, go to Nineveh, the great city, and cry against it,

316
00:19:18,000 --> 00:19:20,000
 for their wickedness has come up before me.'"

317
00:19:20,000 --> 00:19:22,000
 I just want to stop and make a couple of quick observations here

318
00:19:22,000 --> 00:19:24,000
 because in every little bit of Scripture,

319
00:19:24,000 --> 00:19:27,000
 there's something there for you because a lot of people kind of go,

320
00:19:27,000 --> 00:19:29,000
 "Well, man, I'm not like Jonah. This doesn't really apply to me."

321
00:19:29,000 --> 00:19:31,000
 I want to let you know this,

322
00:19:31,000 --> 00:19:35,000
 that there is a responsibility for anybody

323
00:19:35,000 --> 00:19:36,000
 that the word of the Lord has come to.

324
00:19:36,000 --> 00:19:40,000
 Having received grace and mercy,

325
00:19:40,000 --> 00:19:42,000
 having received from God revelation,

326
00:19:42,000 --> 00:19:47,000
 you are necessarily given with that reception some responsibility.

327
00:19:47,000 --> 00:19:49,000
 There's a great question that people often ask.

328
00:19:49,000 --> 00:19:54,000
 "Hey, well, what about people that have never heard the story of Jesus Christ?

329
00:19:54,000 --> 00:19:57,000
 The Bible says there's no other name under heaven by which men must be saved.

330
00:19:57,000 --> 00:20:00,000
 And so what about the un-evangelized heathen?

331
00:20:00,000 --> 00:20:01,000
 Has anybody ever hit you up with that one?

332
00:20:01,000 --> 00:20:03,000
 What about those that have never heard?

333
00:20:03,000 --> 00:20:04,000
 Is there any way that they can be saved?"

334
00:20:04,000 --> 00:20:07,000
 And sometimes people ask that question because they're trying to figure out,

335
00:20:07,000 --> 00:20:10,000
 "Hey, if there's a loophole for that guy, maybe there's a loophole for me."

336
00:20:10,000 --> 00:20:13,000
 And by the way, even if there's no loophole for that guy,

337
00:20:13,000 --> 00:20:16,000
 I think God's unjust if he's going to judge people who are condemned

338
00:20:16,000 --> 00:20:19,000
 because they've rejected a Jesus in whom they've never heard.

339
00:20:19,000 --> 00:20:24,000
 There was a guy who was a great communicator who lived about 150, 160 years ago.

340
00:20:24,000 --> 00:20:26,000
 His name was Spurgeon.

341
00:20:26,000 --> 00:20:30,000
 And Spurgeon was asked the question, "What about the un-evangelized heathen?

342
00:20:30,000 --> 00:20:31,000
 Can they be saved?"

343
00:20:31,000 --> 00:20:33,000
 And Spurgeon's response, I thought, was brilliant.

344
00:20:33,000 --> 00:20:36,000
 By the way, if you're not familiar with a little resource we create around here

345
00:20:36,000 --> 00:20:38,000
 called Real Truth Real Quick, we've answered that question.

346
00:20:38,000 --> 00:20:42,000
 So in five minutes, you can just Google "un-evangelized heathen," "real truth real quick,"

347
00:20:42,000 --> 00:20:45,000
 or "Todd Wagner, un-evangelized heathen."

348
00:20:45,000 --> 00:20:48,000
 Those two things sometimes go together.

349
00:20:48,000 --> 00:20:54,000
 And you'll get a little five-minute response on a biblical perspective on that answer.

350
00:20:54,000 --> 00:20:56,000
 But let me give you this answer tonight,

351
00:20:56,000 --> 00:20:59,000
 because I thought it was brilliant what Spurgeon said when he was asked that question.

352
00:20:59,000 --> 00:21:01,000
 Spurgeon said, "To me, it's a much greater question.

353
00:21:01,000 --> 00:21:04,000
 Can those of us who have heard the gospel

354
00:21:04,000 --> 00:21:11,000
 and refuse to share it with those who have not heard it really be saved?"

355
00:21:11,000 --> 00:21:13,000
 Let me say that again.

356
00:21:13,000 --> 00:21:15,000
 You know, sometimes when people ask you that question,

357
00:21:15,000 --> 00:21:18,000
 what they're really looking for is a loophole themselves, like,

358
00:21:18,000 --> 00:21:21,000
 "Hey, maybe if that guy gets off, I can get off."

359
00:21:21,000 --> 00:21:23,000
 And let me just tell you, the person who's asking you that question,

360
00:21:23,000 --> 00:21:26,000
 whatever is true of the un-evangelized heathen isn't true of them,

361
00:21:26,000 --> 00:21:30,000
 or they wouldn't be asking the question.

362
00:21:30,000 --> 00:21:32,000
 But I'll just give you a little insight real quick.

363
00:21:32,000 --> 00:21:35,000
 The Bible never says that there's anybody anywhere that would be judged

364
00:21:35,000 --> 00:21:37,000
 because they've rejected a Jesus who's never heard.

365
00:21:37,000 --> 00:21:40,000
 The Bible also says that God is just.

366
00:21:40,000 --> 00:21:43,000
 And the Bible does still say that that person who's never heard of Jesus is under judgment

367
00:21:43,000 --> 00:21:45,000
 because of their own conscience they violate,

368
00:21:45,000 --> 00:21:50,000
 and because of the truth they suppress and righteousness revealed by God in all of creation.

369
00:21:50,000 --> 00:21:53,000
 But I will tell you this, if you really care about the un-evangelized heathen,

370
00:21:53,000 --> 00:21:56,000
 the greatest thing that you can do is respond to the message of grace yourself

371
00:21:56,000 --> 00:21:58,000
 and then start to do something about getting the message to them.

372
00:21:58,000 --> 00:22:01,000
 Here's what Jonah chapter 1, verse 1 says.

373
00:22:01,000 --> 00:22:04,000
 Jonah chapter 1, verse 1 says, "The word of the Lord came to Jonah."

374
00:22:04,000 --> 00:22:07,000
 As soon as the word of the Lord came to Jonah, he was a prophet.

375
00:22:07,000 --> 00:22:13,000
 And when this happens, you have great responsibility.

376
00:22:13,000 --> 00:22:19,000
 And it doesn't really matter whether or not you like the people that the message is supposed to go to.

377
00:22:19,000 --> 00:22:21,000
 God calls you to love them.

378
00:22:21,000 --> 00:22:24,000
 In fact, he calls you to suffer for them that they may know.

379
00:22:24,000 --> 00:22:27,000
 And in fact, the more you suffer to take the message to them,

380
00:22:27,000 --> 00:22:31,000
 the more it's a sign for them about how much God loves them.

381
00:22:31,000 --> 00:22:39,000
 This is what was said of Paul when he was talking to the people that were in a certain town at that day called Ephesus.

382
00:22:39,000 --> 00:22:41,000
 And he just said to them, he said, "Hey man, listen.

383
00:22:41,000 --> 00:22:46,000
 Don't you lose heart when you hear about my tribulations, for they are your glory."

384
00:22:46,000 --> 00:22:52,000
 In other words, when you see how much God wants me to suffer just so you can get the message of redemption,

385
00:22:52,000 --> 00:22:54,000
 don't you worry about that.

386
00:22:54,000 --> 00:23:00,000
 In fact, it ought to be a constant reminder of how much God loves you.

387
00:23:00,000 --> 00:23:03,000
 The Bible tells us when we look at how much God loves us,

388
00:23:03,000 --> 00:23:10,000
 that he would take his only begotten son, who is eternally dwelt in glory with the rest of the Godhead,

389
00:23:10,000 --> 00:23:15,000
 and he would not regard equality with God a thing to be grasped, but he emptied himself.

390
00:23:15,000 --> 00:23:25,000
 In other words, he didn't stop being God, but he stopped holding on to his ability to act in a way that his divine, eternal perfection demands and deserves.

391
00:23:25,000 --> 00:23:29,000
 And he humbled himself, and he found himself in the appearance of a man, and being made in the image of a man,

392
00:23:29,000 --> 00:23:32,000
 he became obedient even to the point of death.

393
00:23:32,000 --> 00:23:34,000
 Why? Because God is a just God.

394
00:23:34,000 --> 00:23:41,000
 He in fact will judge sin, but he's a loving God, and so he wants to justify those who deserve judgment.

395
00:23:41,000 --> 00:23:45,000
 God solves this problem by letting himself in the person of his son,

396
00:23:45,000 --> 00:23:55,000
 which is the visible image of the invisible God, go through unspeakable horrors for you.

397
00:23:55,000 --> 00:23:58,000
 And when we see what Christ went through, it's two things.

398
00:23:58,000 --> 00:24:10,000
 It makes you wonder what kind of love is this, and it makes you wonder how valuable are those people that God gave his son for.

399
00:24:10,000 --> 00:24:15,000
 When you look at who the Ninevites were in history, and you see what God's going to do with his prophet,

400
00:24:15,000 --> 00:24:19,000
 now Jonah was not just any prophet. Jonah was already kicking it.

401
00:24:19,000 --> 00:24:22,000
 He had already been faithful as a prophet to Israel.

402
00:24:22,000 --> 00:24:25,000
 His name is mentioned in 2 Kings chapter 14 as the guy who had done his job,

403
00:24:25,000 --> 00:24:29,000
 and God took this effective, faithful prophet, and he said, "Hey, guess what?

404
00:24:29,000 --> 00:24:35,000
 I don't just love folks who speak Hebrew. I love those folks over there that are worshiping, guess what? Dagon.

405
00:24:35,000 --> 00:24:42,000
 Who is Dagon? He is the fish God."

406
00:24:42,000 --> 00:24:49,000
 And so even in Jonah's rebellion, you're going to watch how God works Jonah's rebellion for good

407
00:24:49,000 --> 00:24:53,000
 as a way to either further confirm his message to the Assyrians.

408
00:24:53,000 --> 00:24:57,000
 Now, God didn't want Jonah to rebel, but God's going to work all things for good to those who love God

409
00:24:57,000 --> 00:25:00,000
 and are called according to his purpose.

410
00:25:00,000 --> 00:25:04,000
 Jonah just happened to go through a little bit more heartache because he didn't obey God outright.

411
00:25:04,000 --> 00:25:09,000
 When the word of the Lord comes to you, you are a prophet.

412
00:25:09,000 --> 00:25:12,000
 And I don't really want to hear anything about how you don't think you're gifted,

413
00:25:12,000 --> 00:25:14,000
 how you don't think that you're capable.

414
00:25:14,000 --> 00:25:18,000
 If the word of the Lord comes to you, you are his prophet.

415
00:25:18,000 --> 00:25:24,000
 And if you have profited from the word of God, you carry with that prophet a necessary obligation to help others.

416
00:25:24,000 --> 00:25:30,000
 The reason that you are blessed is to be a blessing,

417
00:25:30,000 --> 00:25:35,000
 not so you can scoff at those who do not have what you have.

418
00:25:35,000 --> 00:25:40,000
 And by the way, you know that if you're blessed, it means you've received something you don't deserve.

419
00:25:40,000 --> 00:25:44,000
 And so the last thing you want to do is look at arrogance with others who didn't receive what you have received.

420
00:25:44,000 --> 00:25:49,000
 The word grace in Greek is the word charis, C-H-A-R-I-S.

421
00:25:49,000 --> 00:25:52,000
 It's where we get the English word charity,

422
00:25:52,000 --> 00:25:58,000
 which means you receive something that you don't earn or deserve.

423
00:25:58,000 --> 00:26:02,000
 And so when you look at other people who don't have what you have,

424
00:26:02,000 --> 00:26:05,000
 the last thing you should do is go, "Well, how come you don't have what I have

425
00:26:05,000 --> 00:26:09,000
 when you have what you have because it was a gift?"

426
00:26:09,000 --> 00:26:16,000
 All we are is individuals who as beggars have received bread that we didn't earn or deserve,

427
00:26:16,000 --> 00:26:19,000
 and what any beggar who has received something they don't deserve should do

428
00:26:19,000 --> 00:26:23,000
 is to tell other people who are hungry where they can receive it.

429
00:26:23,000 --> 00:26:28,000
 I don't ever get discouraged when I come up against people who don't know the kindness of God

430
00:26:28,000 --> 00:26:35,000
 and the goodness of who He is because frankly, I'm not really sure how in my arrogance

431
00:26:35,000 --> 00:26:40,000
 and in my self-sufficiency and in my general prosperity and blessed way

432
00:26:40,000 --> 00:26:45,000
 have come to a point in my life where I really understood my need for God.

433
00:26:45,000 --> 00:26:50,000
 Other than this, the kindness of God let me see that there's lots of ways that seem right to me,

434
00:26:50,000 --> 00:26:52,000
 but they're always going to end in the way of death.

435
00:26:52,000 --> 00:26:56,000
 I love the story of a guy that was a Supreme Court Justice in England,

436
00:26:56,000 --> 00:26:59,000
 and he was a very righteous man, a very philanthropic man.

437
00:26:59,000 --> 00:27:03,000
 He was kind and gracious to many. He was just as a judge,

438
00:27:03,000 --> 00:27:07,000
 and he was a leader and a ruler in his church. He was an elder, if you will.

439
00:27:07,000 --> 00:27:13,000
 He was one time at the communion rail, and next to him, a guy that he had prosecuted

440
00:27:13,000 --> 00:27:20,000
 and that he had actually adjudicated over and had sent to prison took communion next to him.

441
00:27:20,000 --> 00:27:24,000
 Now, this particular distinguished judge was good friends with the rector

442
00:27:24,000 --> 00:27:26,000
 of that particular Episcopal church or Anglican church,

443
00:27:26,000 --> 00:27:30,000
 and they were walking home after that particular Sunday,

444
00:27:30,000 --> 00:27:33,000
 and the rector said to this distinguished judge,

445
00:27:33,000 --> 00:27:36,000
 "Hey, did you see who took communion next to you today?"

446
00:27:36,000 --> 00:27:37,000
 And the judge said, "Yes, I did."

447
00:27:37,000 --> 00:27:42,000
 And the rector said, "What an amazing picture of grace."

